ddress><gtr:line1>University of Leeds</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Leeds</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>West Yorkshire</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>LS2 9JT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Yorkshire and The Humber</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/21509537-6AEE-49B5-BB9A-CDCCF94E018C"><gtr:id>21509537-6AEE-49B5-BB9A-CDCCF94E018C</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Irena</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Grugulis</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF038941%2F1"><gtr:id>5B8D8ACE-8A9C-49FF-9C29-ACD4D9D22F86</gtr:id><gtr:title>Service work: the creative industries</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F038941/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This research project examines two creative industries, film and TV; and digital media, software and computer games.&amp;nbsp; It considers:
&lt;br />
&lt;br />
&lt;ol>
 &lt;li>how people working in creative industries acquire and develop skills;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>the impact of social and reputational capital;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>the way that work is controlled and the role played by managers and leaders.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;br />Skills development is a major challenge in the creative industries.&amp;nbsp; Work demands creativity and skills are often learned during projects, but fragmenting organisations and freelance work may limit opportunities.&amp;nbsp; Social capital serves as a flexible and inexpensive mechanism for recruitment and a guarantor of competence but it also has disadvantages.&amp;nbsp; Management and leadership in this sector is particularly challenging since creative knowledge work requires freedom from control rather than regulation.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The core of this research is participant observation of a single case study company.&amp;nbsp; This will allow in-depth research.&amp;nbsp; Through it, it is also possible to capture the impact of external influences, particularly that of the customer or client.&amp;nbsp; Studies of three internet usenet discussion groups will explore the skills development which occurs outside organisational boundaries, while wider interviews with industry professionals and diary studies of managers will triangulate the detailed ethnographic work with practice elsewhere.
&lt;br />
